Question 1:¶

Recreate the barplot below that shows the population of different continents for the year 2007.

Hints:

  • Extract the 2007 year data from the dataframe. You have to process the data accordingly
  • use plotly bar
  • Add different colors for different continents
  • Sort the order of the continent for the visualisation. Use axis layout setting
  • Add text to each bar that represents the population
In [15]:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Step 1: Filter data for the year 2007
df_2007 = df[df['year'] == 2007]

# Step 2: Aggregate population by continent
continent_population = df_2007.groupby('continent')['pop'].sum().reset_index()

# Step 3: Create the bar plot with Plotly
fig = px.bar(
    continent_population,
    y='continent', 
    x='pop', 
    text='pop', 
    title='Population of Continents in 2007',
    color='continent',
)

# Step 4: Sort continents in the desired order
fig.update_layout(
    yaxis={'categoryorder':'total ascending'},  # Sort the continents by population
    xaxis_title='Population',
    yaxis_title='Continent'
)

# Step 5: Add text annotations (population numbers on top of bars)
fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2s}', textposition='outside')

# Display the plot
fig.show()

Question 4:¶

Thus far we looked at data from one year (2007). Lets create an animation to see the population growth of the continents through the years

In [17]:
# Step 1: Aggregate population by continent and year
continent_population_over_time = df.groupby(['year', 'continent'])['pop'].sum().reset_index()

# Step 2: Create the animated bar plot with Plotly
fig = px.bar(
    continent_population_over_time,
    y='continent', 
    x='pop', 
    color='continent',
    text='pop',
    animation_frame='year',  # Create an animation based on the year
    range_x=[0, continent_population_over_time['pop'].max() * 1.1],  # Set the y-axis range to accommodate changes over years
    title='Population Growth of Continents Through the Years',
)

# Step 3: Add text annotations (population numbers on top of bars)
fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2s}', textposition='outside')

# Step 4: Set axis titles
fig.update_layout(
    xaxis_title='Population',
    yaxis_title='Continent',
    yaxis={'categoryorder': 'total ascending'},  # Sorting by population within each year
)

# Display the animated plot
fig.show()

Question 7:¶

Show only the top 10 countries in the animation

Hint: Use the axis limit to set this.

In [21]:
# Step 1: Aggregate population by country and year
country_population_over_time = df.groupby(['year', 'country'])['pop'].sum().reset_index()

# Step 2: For each year, keep only the top 10 countries by population
top_10_countries = country_population_over_time.groupby('year', group_keys=False).apply(lambda x: x.nlargest(10, 'pop'))

# Step 3: Create the animated bar plot with Plotly, focusing on top 10 countries
fig = px.bar(
    top_10_countries,
    y='country', 
    x='pop', 
    color='country',
    text='pop',
    animation_frame='year',  # Create an animation based on the year
    range_x=[0, top_10_countries['pop'].max() * 1.1],  # Set the y-axis range to accommodate changes over years
    title='Population Growth of Top 10 Countries Through the Years',
)

# Step 4: Add text annotations (population numbers on top of bars)
fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2s}', textposition='outside')

# Step 5: Set axis titles and figure layout, including height adjustment and sorting
fig.update_layout(
    xaxis_title='Population',
    yaxis_title='Country',
    yaxis={'categoryorder': 'total ascending'},  # Sorting by population within each year
    height=1000  # Adjusting the height of the figure
)

# Display the animated plot
fig.show()
